13:
It's down! Whatever you do, don't let
it get away!
19:
You miserable hunk of junk! I'll rip off
your wings one by one!
64:
I should have used the lance's
power earlier... My foolishness
endangered the lives of others.
69:
Don't worry—my man seems to be in
one piece.
72:
You have my thanks for this. Your
deeds saved this soldier's life.
77: That... was one seriously long day.
80:
Everyone's doing their absolute best
to pull this plan off. I'm not alone
here, and I can't act like it.
83:
...Just listen to me. Who the hell do I
think I am, pretending I'm the one in
charge of this whole operation.
When did I get so arrogant?
86:
First, I need to make sure I don't get
in everyone else's way. Before the
battle, I just hope I can beat Celtie in
a duel ONE time. Just once...
89:
I'm not sure I'll be able to sleep
tonight.
93:
Yo, Ayumu. You still awake?
Whatever, I'm coming in.
102:
Hello. Sorry to barge in like this, I'm
sure you must be tired.
107:
Something's got Nova all excited.
Can't stand still for a moment. I
swear, he's like a puppy.
112:
Whatever. You wanna get
something to eat?
116:
I'm honestly in shock. That was my
first time fighting like that—I had no
idea I could even do that.
120:
I mean, we Stellas weren't initially
programmed to have combat
capabilities!
124:
I suppose that means I've gained
some degree of freedom from the
Overlords, doesn't it?
128:
Man, you're STILL going on about
that? That's seriously the only thing
he's talked about since he got back.
133:
Heh, well, you never forget your first
real battle. Can't blame the guy.
136:
Besides, he reminds me of a certain
other brat who couldn't get over
himself after his powers awoke.
142:
Whatever, all guys do that. It's like a
rite of passage! Anyway. Nova, I say
we pull an all-nighter!
147:
It... really did make me happy, you
know. Truly.
150:
Adjudicus, and that fiend
youngster... They thanked me for
aiding them!
154:
Bah, he's exactly the same as Stella
after all, this pretty boy of ours.
157:
Meaning—deep down—he's
basically just a little kid.
162:
I'm reminded of something you said
before.
165:
About giving up on Palpebra. I'm
starting to think you didn't mean it
after all.
172: But it's really not my place to say—
177:
Bah, out with it already! No beating
around the bush or expecting us to
know how you feel! I can't stand that
crap.
180:
If you go around expecting
everyone to read your mind, you're
gonna have a bad time.
188:
You and I are more similar than we
may think, Sho.
193:
Whoa, no need to diss me like that,
man!
197:
Yeah, yeah. How about you watch
where you're walkin', you klutz.
208:
H-hello there! It's been a long time,
hasn't it. Do you remember me, by
any chance?
211:
But of course.
It's been a while, Ayumu.
214:
You're well-acquainted with this
establishment, it seems.
218:
Oh yeah. The two of us are regulars.
Ayumu is crazy about this place—we
only recently found out it survived
the incident, though.
223:
It's easily the best curry place in the
entire world! I'll have a vegetable
curry, please! Oh, for newcomers, I
strongly recommend pork!
228:
D-damn. Man really loves his curry,
huh. Fine, I guess I'll try the pork.
233:
Pork for Nova too. I'll have the
Keema curry.
It's been, what, 2 years since you last
came here, right Ayumu? Maybe
even longer.
236:
Originally this place was only open
for lunch. Then all that crazy stuff
happened and the shop was even
set to close. After Aegis showed up,
though...
239:
We had many young people with no
place to go, and the mayor made a
personal request. Staying open at
night seemed like the right call.
242:
Well, whatever, this delicious curry
isn't gonna eat itself!
250:
I'm in heaven.
I've died and gone to heaven.
There's no other explanation.
254:
Heh. If you love curry so much, why
don't you marry it? Hell, forget
that—you should work at a curry
shop instead!
257:
I mean, I'm talking long-term plans
here. You know, after graduating. At
your age, you'd already be done
exams, right?
262:
After graduating... I mean, it's not like
there are any universities left. I'm not
sure this is the time to be thinking
about that.
267:
There's nothing wrong with
contemplating the future. Maybe an
omelet shop would suit you better?
272:
But... I still have so many things left
to do.
277:
Don't be an idiot. Leave the fussing
and planning to the old farts. Focus
on yourself.
282:
Well... In that case...
Yeah, I could see myself working at
a curry place.
287:
But wouldn't you say omelets are
your real specialty?
292:
Fine—an omelet curry restaurant it
is, then.
297:
Oh, speaking of the future, I had
something else to talk to you about.
300:
Our summer vacay. How's about
you and me take a trip to Paradise
Isle!
303:
I flat-out refuse to die before seeing
Marina in a swimsuit. Can we move
that final battle back a teensy bit?
308:
You want me to postpone the battle
for the fate of the world... for THAT?
318:
*yawn*
I am seriously beat. When we get
home, I'm passing out.
326:
When we're done with this whole
mess, there's one more little thing I
want to take care of. You know what
I'm talking about, right?
338:
Relax, I'm kidding—well, sorta. You've
got yourself a few pretty good
reasons to come back alive, if you
know what I mean.
341:
Don't forget 'em, eh? All those lovely
ladies.
346: Pot calling the kettle black much?
356:
You're doing this whole "older
brother who knows better" bit—when
really you're just as clueless as me.
359:
We're friends—and that means we're
equals. And in case you forgot,
you've got "girl problems" of your
own.
364:
Heh. I hadn't forgotten. You got me
there.
367:
Fine then, pal. Let's make this
happen, our way. Just like old times.
376:
Before I knew it, summer had
passed, and fall not long after it.
378:
It was winter again. How many
winters had it been?
I could hardly remember.
